It's best to have a mechanic do this both for maximum safety and to ensure safe refrigerant disposal. Your mechanic will know the required EPA procedures for removing and getting rid of old refrigerant. Have the mechanic remove any remaining mineral oil from the system. Make sure that the mechanic flushes the system with a solvent that's compatible with R-134a. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/97/Retrofit-Air-Conditioning-in-Cars-to-New-Refrigerant-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Retrofit-Air-Conditioning-in-Cars-to-New-Refrigerant-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/97/Retrofit-Air-Conditioning-in-Cars-to-New-Refrigerant-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Retrofit-Air-Conditioning-in-Cars-to-New-Refrigerant-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

The mineral oil that is put back into your system should match the old oil. If you had PAG oil, then the mechanic should use PAG oil again. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/02/Retrofit-Air-Conditioning-in-Cars-to-New-Refrigerant-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Retrofit-Air-Conditioning-in-Cars-to-New-Refrigerant-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/02/Retrofit-Air-Conditioning-in-Cars-to-New-Refrigerant-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Retrofit-Air-Conditioning-in-Cars-to-New-Refrigerant-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

The desiccant helps to remove moisture that may accumulate in your A/C system. If your A/C system uses an accumulator, you'll find it at the evaporator outlet. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/f\/f1\/Retrofit-Air-Conditioning-in-Cars-to-New-Refrigerant-Step-2Bullet1.jpg\/v4-460px-Retrofit-Air-Conditioning-in-Cars-to-New-Refrigerant-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/f\/f1\/Retrofit-Air-Conditioning-in-Cars-to-New-Refrigerant-Step-2Bullet1.jpg\/v4-760px-Retrofit-Air-Conditioning-in-Cars-to-New-Refrigerant-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

You'll find the receiver-drier in systems that use an expansion valve to control refrigerant flow. It's connected to the high-pressure liquid line, between the condenser and the expansion valve. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/2\/2b\/Retrofit-Air-Conditioning-in-Cars-to-New-Refrigerant-Step-2Bullet2.jpg\/v4-460px-Retrofit-Air-Conditioning-in-Cars-to-New-Refrigerant-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/2\/2b\/Retrofit-Air-Conditioning-in-Cars-to-New-Refrigerant-Step-2Bullet2.jpg\/v4-760px-Retrofit-Air-Conditioning-in-Cars-to-New-Refrigerant-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Make sure that your desiccant is compatible with R-134a refrigerant.

Do this even if you don't think that you need to replace them so that you don't have to do it later if they don't seal. When you remove an old O-ring, tape it to a piece of paper. Write down exactly where that O-ring came from and keep the papers for a while. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2f/Retrofit-Air-Conditioning-in-Cars-to-New-Refrigerant-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Retrofit-Air-Conditioning-in-Cars-to-New-Refrigerant-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2f/Retrofit-Air-Conditioning-in-Cars-to-New-Refrigerant-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Retrofit-Air-Conditioning-in-Cars-to-New-Refrigerant-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If you have a leak at a connection, grab the O-ring that you took replaced. Double-check to make sure that you replaced the old O-ring with a new O-ring that was the right size. Most A/C leaks are caused by O-rings that aren't properly installed. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b7/Retrofit-Air-Conditioning-in-Cars-to-New-Refrigerant-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Retrofit-Air-Conditioning-in-Cars-to-New-Refrigerant-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b7/Retrofit-Air-Conditioning-in-Cars-to-New-Refrigerant-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Retrofit-Air-Conditioning-in-Cars-to-New-Refrigerant-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
